In the world of finance, Open API stands for a technological revolution. This SFTI video shows how it works, and gives you a taste of the future of banking and finance in Switzerland.
Cortet et al. (2016) note that a pivotal element to the concept of opening up payment accounts is the development of APIs by banks. Fintech players are seeking to capitalise on the emerging API landscape and to capture customer and developer mindshare as well as payment and non-payment (data rich service) revenues, long taken for granted by incumbent financial institutions. The key challenge for leaders of incumbent financial institutions is to ensure PSD2 “Access to Account” (XS2A) compliance, while at the same time retaining customer relevance and maximising addressable market and revenue potential across a rich transaction services portfolio. The authors go on to suggest that APIs could redefine the financial services distribution game of banks as new routes to market become possible.
Deloitte (2016) outlines some of the key considerations which the EBA has had to take into account in the development of regulatory technical standards surrounding the PSD2 regulations:

Strong customer authentication, and exemptions to this in certain circumstances;
Safety of consumer funds and personal data;
Fair competition between payers, and business model and technology agnosticism;
Risk associated with different technology and transaction types;
Flexibility to enable and support innovation in payments;
Monitoring and updating of regulatory technical standards on an ongoing basis;
Ability to differentiate between consumer initiated and PISP initiated payments;
Ensure incumbent banks communicate securely with PISPs;
Ensure incumbent banks make all available information available to PISPs around a payment order;
Ensure incumbent banks do not discriminate between internal and PISP initiated payment transactions.
While the PSD2 regulations promote that banks must provide access to customer information, they do not prescribe the details of the APIs that third parties will use to connect with banks. For example, the Regulatory Technical Standards on strong customer authentication specifies only technical framework conditions and no interface standard. Consequently, a number of independent standards are evolving across Europe
For a more technical discussion of the role of APIs, check out this webinar on PSD2 Open Banking with APIs brought to you by Fiorano Software.

